  "prompt": "Is it likely that stem cell tooth regeneration will be possible by next year (2017)?",
  "response": "As of the latest available information, complete stem cell tooth regeneration had not been achieved by 2016, and it is unlikely to be fully realized by 2017. While there has been significant progress in stem cell research and regenerative medicine, developing fully functional, bioengineered teeth from stem cells remains a complex challenge.\n\nResearchers have made advances in understanding how stem cells can be used to regenerate dental tissues such as dentin, enamel, and pulp. Preliminary studies and experimental treatments have shown promising results in animal models and early human trials. However, translating these findings into a safe, reliable, and widely available clinical treatment involves overcoming numerous biological, technical, and regulatory hurdles.\n\nTherefore, while progress continues to be made, the timeline for practical application of stem cell tooth regeneration in humans is difficult to predict and likely still several years away from being a routine dental treatment.",
